[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Java serialization**\n\nI'm thinking about how the custom ObjectInputStream's resolveClass might be returning a publicKeyClass that could be non-public. It seems like ObjectStreamClass handles non-public no-arg classes. If that's true, Java serialization needs to reflectively invoke the first non-serializable superclass constructor (which is Object), and there's a chance that's not being registered properly. It's tricky when dealing with these classes!\n\n**Evaluating serialization tests**\n\nAll top tests are running under Native. I'm considering using the GraalVM SDK with `@RegisterForReflection`, but I might need additional dependencies. It's tricky since I cannot annotate `java.lang.Object`. Maybe the simplest solution is not to deserialize fully but just serialize to cover `writeObject`. The report indicates that `writeObject` isn't covered because native might abort before coverage is flushed. If I split tests, perhaps one method will serialize correctly, but I need to figure out why serialization-only isn’t enough.\n\n**Assessing serialization issues**\n\nThe test's serialization might call `ObjectOutputStream.writeObject0`, which would invoke the `writeObject` method. Inside that, it calls `out.writeObject(baseKey.getAlgorithm())`, which should be covered. Maybe there's an issue if `baseKey.getAlgorithm()` returns a class that uses `writeReplace`. I’m also wondering if the generated provider key class wasn’t `ProvDHPublicKey`. The test XML specifies the class name, and it asserted that it passed in the JVM, but I see that native fails after serialization, so the write path should be covered.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0a88e4936db2e709016a3f8d779790819797a9b8f29114f8af\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqP42J6LkWKWddmRLQJLs-6dq3b4vwUV6OHTCCk2bpFStUQKj5Ssa0UGSlpLBbL1NmL7qgKPlIhNJmKsKN7wNxBKo8R1GP