rIgIhiB44GJnonmR5olaJ_JWk2-27bFw1M5iyuFHORh1Zs-vwSPIUY8Vokc8JmxQub2Ejpi7tslZOLxKpwh5U30n2Luw-GB4UiGWV5IcOJ5FZrgS6iWhCajuTDAjPbR3IOk8AcKp5x_Vi_rIqjFZLFgKF1bN837sQ_lXxcSsywc5RORg5OT_wIC0FJBHcEoE2GpfY1TEdgPPIwtcnY5R6Asc\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Java serialization**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how the custom ObjectInputStream's resolveClass might be returning a publicKeyClass that could be non-public. It seems like ObjectStreamClass handles non-public no-arg classes. If that's true, Java serialization needs to reflectively invoke the first non-serializable superclass constructor (which is Object), and there's a chance that's not being registered properly. It's tricky when dealing with these classes!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating serialization tests**\\n\\nAll top tests are running under Native. I'm considering using the GraalVM SDK with `@RegisterForReflection`, but I might need additional dependencies. It's tricky since I cannot annotate `java.lang.Object`. Maybe the simplest solution is not to deserialize fully but just serialize to cover `writeObject`. The report indicates that `writeObject` isn't covered because native might abort before coverage is flushed. If I split tests, perhaps one method will serialize correctly, but I need to figure out why serialization-only isn’t enough.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing serialization issues**\\n\\nThe test's serialization might call `ObjectOutputStream.writeObject0`, which would invoke the `writeObject` method. Inside that, it calls `out.writeObject(baseKey.getAlgorithm())`, which should be covered. Maybe there's an issue if `baseKey.getAlgorithm()` returns a class that uses `writeReplace`. I’m also wondering if the generated provider key class wasn’t `ProvDHPublicKey`. The test XML specifies the class name, and it asserted that it passed in the JVM, but I see that native fails after serialization, so the write path should be covered.\"}]}"},